The malicious flash file 8hthrx.swf (MD5 faa74be286c58be616470558d78a137f) checks the user's operating system (OS) and browser version. If the OS is Windows XP, it targets either Firefox or Internet Explorer; otherwise it only targets Internet Explorer.
The file (MD5 faa74be286c58be616470558d78a137f) was LZMA compressed and the payload was obfuscated using a one byte XOR key. Underlying the XOR is an embedded executable and the following callback URLs.
http://iad12s04-in-f22.1h100.net http://iad12s04-in-f22.1h100.net/pv.png http://iad12s04-in-f22.1h100.net/cmd_postback.php http://iad12s04-in-f22.1h100.net/init_postback.php http://iad12s04-in-f99.1h100.net/pv.png
It was reported that the malware (MD5 faa74be286c58be616470558d78a137f) triggered an alert on the following yara rules: UNKNOWN_INDICATOR_IMPLANT_ADVIEPACK { strings: $STR1 = "File %s downloaded." $STR2 = "Failed to axel." $STR3 = "%s=%s&%s=%s" condition: (uint16(0) == 0x5A4D) and all of them }
unknown_indiciator_technique_map_dll { strings: $Loader = {55 8B EC 51 51 8B 45 08 B9 4D 5A 00 00 66 39 08 74 04 33 C0 C9 C3 53 8B 58 3C 03 D8 81 3B 50 45 00 00 74 07 33 C0 E9 ?? ?? ?? ?? 56 8B 35 ?? ?? ?? ?? 57 6A 04 BF 00 20 00 00} condition: (uint16(0) == 0x5A4D) and all of them }

The email body contained a link that directs to:
http://gallosport.com/list/default.html?<UNIQUE ID>

The malware associated with this activity may be a CTFMON variant.  The suspected variant may be detected with the following rules provided by the reporting U.S. government agency:

To detect the invalid X-Mailers used in this campaign (note that spam, in addition to spear-phishing will also be detected), the following SNORT signature may be used:

alert tcp any any -> any any (msg:"INVALID_XMAILER_MS_OUTLOOK_5589"; sid:
12345; content:"X-Mailer: Microsoft Outlook Express 6.00.2900.5589";)

If the same first stage implant is being used in this campaign, as in a previous campaign, activity involving the CTFMON Version 4 implant can be identified using the following signatures:

alert tcp any any <> any $HTTP_PORTS (msg:"CTFMONv4_DROPPER_CALLOUT";
flow:established,to_server; content:"GET"; http_method; content:"/blk"; http_uri;
pcre:"/^\/blk\d{2}\.htm$/U"; sid:1234;)

alert tcp any any -> any $WEB_PORTS (msg:"CTFMONv4_IMPLANT_CALLOUT"; sid:1234;
flow:established,to_server; content:"GET"; http_method; content:"/xdot/index";
fast_pattern: only; http_uri; pcre:"/^\/xdot\/index(?:1|33|34)_[0-9]{1,16}\.html$/U";)

Once the malware is executed on the victim system, the malware attempts a call back to the hard-coded IP 89.238.150.154 via TCP, and also via ICMP (Ping/Pong). If communication is successful, it attempts to connect to another command and control (C2) server via the hard-coded IP address 108.162.197.26. The malware will accept the following commands, all preceded with the ! symbol: !* PING; waits for a reply of "PONG!" and if received connects to second IP address for C2 !* SH; Execute a shell command !* GETLOCALIP; Retrieves the local IP address of the victim system !* SCANNER ON | OFF; Scan networks !* LOLNOGTFO; Terminate backdoor.
Additional commands used for DDoS: !* HOLD; Hold flooding !* JUNK; Perform junk flood !* UDP; Perform udp flood !* TC; Perform tcp flood !* KILLATTK; Kill all flood
If the scanner detects that a device has telnet enabled, it will attempt a limited brute force login using vendor default passwords, to include: "root", "admin", "user", "login", "guest", "toor", "guest", "changeme", "1234", "12345", "123456", "default", "pass" and "password".
A variation of the following yara signature can be used to detect this malware: rule Bash_nginx_backdoor {
strings: $a1 = "JUNK Flooding %s:%d for %d seconds." $a2 = "UDP Flooding %s for %d seconds." $a3 = "UDP Flooding %s:%d for %d seconds." $a4 = "TCP Flooding %s for %d seconds." $a5 = "KILLATTK" $a6 = "REPORT %s:%s:" $a7 = "PING" $a8 = "PONG!" $a9 = "GETLOCALIP" $a10 = "SCANNER" condition: all of them }

